{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657799"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:35:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:35:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20650"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20650","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20650"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.91,0.05,0,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13526"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95004"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13526","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13526"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20650"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77978"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10955"},{"type":"tags","id":"11585"},{"type":"tags","id":"11789"},{"type":"tags","id":"12537"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32302"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32303"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95004","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95004"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents with a painful, fluctuant swelling on her right thigh that has been enlarging over the past three days. On examination, the area is erythematous, warm, and tender. Incision and drainage of the lesion yields thick, yellow-white fluid.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathophysiology of this inflammatory process?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Granulomatous reaction with epithelioid macrophages","Localised collection of pus with central liquefaction","Fibrinous exudate on serosal surfaces","Caseous necrosis with minimal neutrophil infiltration","Accumulation of fibrin and platelets in tissue spaces"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has an abscess, which is characterised by a \u003Cstrong\u003Elocalised collection of pus with central liquefaction\u003C/strong\u003E. Abscesses typically form when pyogenic bacteria (pus-producing bacteria) such as \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E are introduced into tissue. The pathophysiology involves:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EA central liquefied region composed of necrotic leucocytes and tissue cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EA surrounding zone of viable neutrophils\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAn outer region showing vascular dilatation and evidence of chronic inflammation and repair\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EEventually, the abscess may become walled off by fibrous tissue\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranulomatous reaction with epithelioid macrophages\u003C/strong\u003E - This is characteristic of chronic granulomatous inflammation seen in conditions like tuberculosis, not acute suppurative inflammation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrinous exudate on serosal surfaces\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes fibrinous inflammation that occurs on serosal surfaces such as the pleura or pericardium, not the liquefactive process of abscess formation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECaseous necrosis with minimal neutrophil infiltration\u003C/strong\u003E - This is typical of tuberculosis and other granulomatous diseases, not the neutrophil-rich suppurative inflammation of an abscess\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAccumulation of fibrin and platelets in tissue spaces\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes thrombosis or fibrinous inflammation, not the suppurative process seen in abscess formation\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPurulent inflammation is characterised by the production of pus, which consists of neutrophils, liquefied debris of necrotic cells, and oedema fluid. The most common causes are pyogenic bacteria that induce liquefactive tissue necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Purulent inflammation is characterised by the production of pus, which consists of neutrophils, liquefied debris of necrotic cells, and oedema fluid.","Pyogenic bacteria like staphylococci cause purulent inflammation by inducing liquefactive tissue necrosis.","Abscesses are localised collections of pus in tissues, organs, or confined spaces that develop a characteristic zonal pattern of inflammation and repair."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair; p. 94"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77978"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20650"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77978"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-26T20:50:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-26T20:52:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13526"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95004"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10955","links":{"self":"https: